Causeway
A warm winter's night in the ancient cityof Alexandria, on the Heptastaddion causeway across the harbour to the Island of Pharos (to north). The Mediterranean waters lap against the land bridge, and the whole city (southeast) is lit up with torches: it is a night of celebration.

Austin, your incorrigible ginger cat, lounges around here.

Austin springs about cheerfully.

===========
==>STEP NUM: 701
==>ACT: north
==>OBSERVATION: Island of Pharos
The island of the Pharos: the lighthouse after which others are named, one ofhe Seven Wonders of the World,d, blazes into the sharp moonlit sky. It is 120 metres high, a circle on an octagon on a square.

A light wind blows across the coastal defences. On this spot, seventy-two scholars first translated the Old Testament into Greek: shivering continuously if it was as chilly as this. A narrow causeway runs south across the harbour.

In one wall of the wave defences is a rusty seaweed-wreathed iron grating, closed up tight.

Interestingly, a key which looks as if it would fit the grating can be seen inside the passage beneath.

Austin strolls regally along with you.

